Religious games, called Ludi Tarentini, Terentini, or Taurii, had been held in Rome from an early period ol the Republic. Their origin is variously stated, though the most probable mythical accounts agree that they were instituted and devoted to Dis and Proserpina in consequence ol a searsul plagae—whether by one Valerius in gratitude sor the recovery of his three children, or in the reign ol Tarquinius Superbus in order to propitiate those sormidable deities. In the latter case the plague had affected pregnant women, and their children died in the womb ; and sterile cows (Taurea) being sacrificed, the gemes were called Ludi 'l‘aurii By . these accounts it would seem that the games were connected with the health of offspring, and by all accounts that they were instituted in honor ol Dis and Proserpina. To mose eminent scholars who hold to the Etrurian origin ol the Tarquins, “the Tarenti and Taurii are but as different forms of the· same word, and of the same root as Tarquinius ” (Smith's Dict, art. “Ludi Saeculares''). Il so, the deities honored were doubtless Etrurian-not Greek nor Roman— though the Romans subsequently identified them with divini· ties familiar to their own worship.

Be that as it may, during the Republic these gemes appear to have been only celebrated three times at irregular intervals in no way connected with fixed periods or cycles (saecula).
